J. B. Rainsberger wrote:

&gt; popmanse wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; If you define an interface, what is the best strategy to test all
&gt; &gt; implementing classes.
&gt;
&gt; Google Abstract Test Case, and especially read any hits at c2.com.


I often use the Parameterized Test Case instead. Just give an instance 
of each class as a parameter. It allows me to test several classes that 
implement the same interface in just one test case; with the Abstract 
Test Case pattern you have to write a test case for every class.

Here&#39;s a simplified example:

   import junit.framework.*;
   import com.zoo.Animals.*;

   public class AnimalTest extends TestCase {

       private Animal animal;
       private int nrLegs;

       public AnimalTest(String testName, Animal animal, int nrLegs) {
           super(testName);
           this.animal = animal;
           this.nrLegs = nrLegs;
      }
      public static Test suite() {
          TestSuite suite = new TestSuite(&quot;Number of legs&quot;);
          suite.addTest(new AnimalTest(&quot;Chicken&quot;, new Chicken(), 2));
          suite.addTest(new AnimalTest(&quot;Cat&quot;, new Cat(), 4));
          suite.addTest(new AnimalTest(&quot;Fly&quot;, new Fly(), 6));
          suite.addTest(new AnimalTest(&quot;Spider&quot;, new Spider(), 8));
          return suite;
      }
      public void runTest() throws Throwable {
           assertTrue(nrLegs==animal.getNrLegs());
      }
   }


However, it shouldn&#39;t be used in every case. If you want to test 
behavior that is specific to one or more classes, but not all, you&#39;ll 
need the Abstract Test Case. Also, if an interface is implemented by 
many classes in different projects, e.g. Enumerator, it shouldn&#39;t be 
used either; I don&#39;t know why, it just feels bad :-).

